post_text:
Attention all 5th/6th volleyball player and parents-

Just a reminder that registration forms and payment is due THIS week, August 28th (extended to Friday, since we have school that day) . I have been in communication with the other area league commissioners. We are attempting to put together a schedule and will relay that info as soon as I can. Once I have all the registration forms, I can let them know how many teams we have and get us divided (if more than 1 team). I have had a few forms come to my home, thus far no coaches, so parents please be thinking if you're willing to help coach. I will get with the coaches soon to discuss practices and the season.

WYAA is looking for new volunteers to join our team. If you're interested please do not hesitate to reach out. WYAA meets the second Wednesday of each month @ 6pm, either at the HS lunch room or recently via Zoom.

If there are questions please do not hesitate to email, text, or call me.
joshmissy09@gmail.com
319-750-2106

WACO Elementary
August 4 at 2:59 PM ·

WACO Elem Families:

We will have CHROMEBOOK RETURN for students who borrowed for the summer on next Monday, August 10 during summer school hours.

If your student used a Chromebook this summer please do drop it off between 8:30 and 11:30 on Monday. You may drive through the pick-up lane to do so. Our amazing technology staff need to make updates and prepare these for use again this year.

If you are unable to come Monday please call the office or email Mrs. Settles to make other arrangements.

Thank you, and don't forget your charger! :)

Class Registration. Students only. Parents wait outside.

9-12 Class Registration will be August 4 and August 5 at the High School. (This is not school registration, but registration so students can choose their classes.)

12th Grade: August 4th- 9-10 AM
11th Grade: August 4th- 10-11 AM
10th Grade: August 4th- 11AM-Noon
9th Grade: August 4th- 1-2 PM

All grades make-up date: August 5 from 9 a.m.-Noon
All sessions will be in the cafeteria. Enter through the main entrance and someone will greet you.
If you cannot make either date, please email Mrs. Pullis!

7th & 8th Grade: Schedules will be loaded and Mrs. Pullis will be in contact with you about band/chorus/orchestra participation. You will not need to come to register. Mrs. Pullis will be in contact with you.

WACO Elementary
June 29 at 6:59 PM ·

WACO Families,

Please check your email for an important survey that our administrative and leadership teams will utilize to help us plan for fall!

We know many of you have questions and concerns. We do too. This information will help us to better understand and address them. Thank you for your continued support and your patience as we work to make the best plan possible for WACO staff and students.

We hope you are all well and enjoying summer! We miss you!

Familias de WACO,
¡Por Favor Consulte su correo electrónico para obtener una encuesta importante que utilizarán nuestros equipos administrativos y de liderazgo para ayudarnos a planificar el otoño!

Sabemos que muchos de ustedes tienen preguntas e inquietudes. Nosotros también. Esta información nos ayudará a comprenderlos y abordarlos mejor. Gracias por su continuo apoyo y su paciencia mientras trabajamos para hacer el mejor plan posible para el personal y los estudiantes de WACO.

¡Esperamos que estén bien y que disfruten del verano! ¡Te extrañamos!

The WACO Foundation hosted a Golf Get Together on Saturday at the Heritage Oaks Golf and Country Club. Here are a few photos from Stacy Peterson and the list of prize winners:

1st Flight: 65
Marcus Davis
Tyler Haigst
Eric Davis
Jeff Hough

2nd Flight: 68
Christian Roth
Jackson Roth
Kendall Leichty
Zack Davis

3rd Flight: 73
Russ Yoder
Tim Meyer
Calvin Bruce
Tim Graber

Longest Drive Men - Drew Burnham
Longest Drive Women - Brittany Burnham
Shortest Drive - Kendall Leichty
Closest to the Pin - Tyler Haigst
Longest Putt - Sid Brooks

Winner of a Free Membership to Heritage Oaks - Lori Miller

There were 14 teams that golfed.

Thanks to Staci Petersen, Shari Janecek, and Lisa Graber for providing supper after golfing, and Greg and Carol Graber and Don Yoder for grilling the turkey tenderloins.

Look forward to next year!

Summer Registration – Fall Flag Football 2020
All 1st – 4th graders for the 2020-2021 school year, we want you to join our program for Flag Football. Flag football is a great introduction to football. Flag football is played without pads and no tackling is allowed. Fun for boys and girls that want to have a better understanding of the sport, or just want to be active.

A registration form was sent to parent emails listed in PowerSchool. If you did not receive the information, send an email to ParentLetter@wacocsd.org.

shared_text:
Waco High
May 28 at 7:42 PM ·

After a lot of thought, conversations, and planning we have decided to cancel Prom and all events associated.

We put students in front of all of our decisions so please know that this wasn't an easy decision to make. We worked very hard to pull it off but we are not in an environment where it would still be meaningful and memorable for students.

I appreciate your flexibility in dealing with information releases about Prom and for everyone who worked hard throughout the year to offer kids the best.

As we move forward we will work to offer seniors a memorable send-off, and we will continue to put what's best for students first in our decisions.

Thank you,

Tim Bartels

Summer Driver Education 2020 Informational Meeting
When: June 1st
Where: High School Gym (socially distanced)
What time: 5:00 pm
What will be discussed: We will explain how the course will be operated, expectations, and answer questions that you may have.
If you plan to take this course, please do the following steps:
1. Pay for the course online through PaySchool ($235.00). 2. Have a valid driving permit.
3. Email Mr. Dugger at mark.dugger@wacocsd.org and he will deliver your packet to your home so that you can get an early start on the classroom work.

Please feel free to contact him with any questions or concerns you may have

Our next Spectacular Senior is Kinzey Miller. She is the daughter of BJ & Jana Miller. Her siblings are Whitney, Walker, Delaney, and Jaicey.

Kinzey's activities included track, football manager, Bethel MYF, and chorus. She plans to attend Kirkwood Community College in the fall for Liberal Arts.

Kinzey's suggestion for a mandatory class for high schoolers is "definitely some sort of finance class to prepare you for moving out of your parents basement."

This Spectacular Senior is Katherine Hallett, daughter of Cynthia Hallett and Lee & Mindy Hallett. Her siblings are Ashleigh, Deacon, William, and

Katherine predicts that in 10 years she will be a long way from Iowa.
She hopes to be traveling the world, maybe on a world tour.

Today's Spectacular Senior is Hannah Boshart, daughter of Steven Boshart, Beth Boshart, and Christina Boshart-Sheetz. Her siblings are Brody Hesser, Lillee Boshart, Chase Boshart, and Zoe-Jane Sheetz.

Hannah's activities included football Manager and boys basketball manager. She plans to attend Kirkwood Community College to major in Human Services.

Here is Hannah's favorite WACO memory: My sophomore year when I first started football managing, Kinzey Miller and I stayed at the practice field after the players had left to drive around In the Gator and pick up the water bottles they left all over the field. I didn’t get hurt, but we both died laughing.

post_text:
It's Maysan Lee's turn in the senior spotlight! Maysan is the daughter of Shane & Bobbi Lee.

She was involved in Iowa High School Rodeo, Basketball, Volleyball, 4-H, and Orchestra. After graduating from WACO, Maysan plans to attend a community college in Texas or Kansas to study athletic training. She will continue her rodeo career on a college rodeo scholarship. After community college, she plans to transfer to a 4-year college to get her master's in athletic training.

Maysan's favorite WACO memory is seeing all the classes and staff come together and celebrate by dressing up, going to Boom Night, and attending the dances during Homecoming each year.

shared_text:
WACO Elementary
April 2 at 4:25 PM ·

Today is the day, we are SO excited for our edarap! (That's parade in reverse! 😂)

We hope to see you, from a distance please, between 4:30 and 5pm!

To note:
1. Our staff will be well spread out and lined up along Main Street and in front of the building.
2. Please drive or walk by and wave, cheer, shout hello, etc.
3. We would ask that you stay in your vehicles and keep your distance.
4. As much as we want to give hugs, high fives and fist bumps to everyone, we take the current health concerns seriously and do not want to put anyone at risk. Again, we ask that you take proper precautions including a minimum of 6 feet of distance and no contact with others.

We love and miss you all and hope to see later!!

💙👏🏾😁

March 30 at 1:31 PM ·

Are you a WACO grad? We want to see how big Warrior Nation is! Drop your City and State in the comment section below. Do we have a Warrior in all 50 states? SHARE!

Edit: Wow! Keep them coming! Here is an interactive map of all WACO Grads across the US! *These will be updated as they come in!

Edit #2: All have been updated. This map looks awesome! Be sure to zoom out to see the out of country Warriors! We will continue to update as they come in. #WeAreWACO.... and we are EVERYWHERE!

Students and ONE adult per family may come and get books, materials, and personal items. They can also check out a Chromebook if you have no other devices in the home.

post_text:
WACO Families, Beginning Monday, March 23 WACO will offer two meals per day to each child (under 18 years of age) free of charge.

In order to assist us please complete this survey by 9:00 p.m. 3/18/2020.
https://tinyurl.com/WACOMealSurvey

This is a free service to all WACO children 18 years of age and younger AND includes any children living in your home even if they do not attend WACO. We will offer curbside pick up at both of our buildings.

1. For WACO students INSIDE the city limits of Wayland and Crawfordsville, we will offer a grab and go.
2. WACO Students that live outside of the city limits may be eligible for delivery.
3.WACO students living outside school district lines (open enrolled students) please complete the survey and we will reach out to you specifically.

Additional information will follow.

Your patience is appreciated as we navigate this new service. Changes will be communicated as quickly as possible.
Go, Warriors!

Member Monday Spotlight - WACO

WACO, Wayland can be found in Henry County. The school is made of the students from the communities of Wayland, Crawfordsville, Olds, Swedesburg, Coppock and Noble. The Warriors are members of the Southeast Iowa Superconference.

IGHSAU Did You Know? WACO earned a Class 1A state track and field team championship in 1989.

shared_text:
WACO Elementary
February 13 at 2:00 PM ·

No School for WACO 2/13/20.

Mrs. Settles' singing voice is a bit rusty. However she would like to share her snow day announcement lyrics with you... maybe we will have to record Mrs. Langr or Mrs. Barnhart next time!

(Sing to the tune of Adele's "Hello From the Other Side")

Hello? It's me.
I'm standing here, out in this complete mysery
because. you need. to know it's another day at home.

Hello? Can ya hear me?
I'm in southeast Iowa dreaming about what Spring used to be...
We were warmer, and free,
I've forgotten how it felt before our toes began to freeze...

Theres such a difference, between us, and a million. Degrees....

Hello from the WACO siiiide
It feels like a slip and sliddddeee
But I know you'll stay warm wherever you are...
Please dont, leave the house, or drive very farrr

Hello from the outsiiiide
I'm glad were not at school this tiiiiimmmmeee
I'll tell you it's so cold, that my lips are numb,
To have busses or recess, would simply be dumb...ohhh kidsss

Hello? It's me.

Friday, Jan. 31, WACO Varsity Basketball competes in the Southeast Iowa Super Conference "Shootout".

This is a varsity only event that matches the 1st place team in the South Division vs. the 1st place team in North Division, #2 vs #2, #3 vs. #3, etc....

The #1 and #2 seeds play at Iowa Wesleyan University, the #3-#9 teams play at North Division schools.

WACO will be playing Columbus at 6pm at Highland High School. Highland vs. Danville will be the 2nd game of the night. Admission is $5 for Adults and Students.

On Wednesday, February 5th from 3:00 PM to 6:00 PM, Southeastern Community College will again be one of the sites for a FAFSA Ready Iowa event. FAFSA Ready Iowa is a program in which volunteers provide free, on-site assistance to families in filing the FAFSA (Free Application for Federal Student Aid), the federally required form for students seeking financial aid for college.

Members of the Financial Aid Office staff will be helping families complete the FAFSA at both the West Burlington and Keokuk campuses throughout the afternoon and evening.

Invitation to sing with the WACO CHOIRS in Concert

You are invited to sing along on the finale of the February 24th WACO concert with the junior high and high school singers. The song is "He Never Failed Me Yet". This has become a tradition at WACO with this favorite piece ending the concert every two years.

Rehearsal times are:
Mondays 12:20-12:50

The concert will be Monday, Feb. 24th at 6:30 p.m.

Any questions, contact Mrs. Koch - jane.koch@wacocsd.org or call the High School office.

Please join us!

Saturday, December 21st WACO basketball participated in Community Night. To celebrate the creation of WACO.

Crawfordsville Cyclones, Olds Raiders, and the Wayland Bombers were the original schools and mascots. Each player wore the shirt from their "hometown." Even the school colors are accurate. WACO was formed in 1962 when the three schools became the WACO Warriors.

Catch Warrior Basketball in action this FRIDAY night, 1/3 at home against the New London Tigers.

JV Boys: 4:30 p.m.*
Freshman Boys: 6:00 p.m.
Varsity Girls: 6:00 p.m.
Varsity Boys: 7:30 p.m.

*No JV Girls game tonight

#wearewaco #buildingalegacy #getthatdub

post_text:
Do your children know bus safety?

Here are a few tips from the Iowa State Patrol.

Bus Stop Rules For the Kids
• Stop and look both ways before crossing any street.
• Getting on or off the bus, do not cross the street until the bus driver signals it’s ok to cross.
• Always cross in front of the bus far enough ahead to be seen by the driver (5 giant steps ahead).
• Never cross behind the bus or run behind the bus.
• Do not run, push or shove when waiting at the bus
stop, and always arrive a few minutes early.
• Wait until the bus driver brings the bus to a complete
stop before attempting to get on the bus.
• Never pick up anything dropped near the bus; tell the
bus driver and follow his or her directions.
• Never crawl under a bus.

#WeAreWACO #warriorpride #buildingalegacy

9 best ways to avoid the germs:

1. Wash your hands
2. Don't share
3. Cover sneezes and coughs- properly. Do the Dab
4. Don't touch your face
5. Skip the water fountain and use a water bottle instead
6.Eat your fruits and veggies
7. Get plenty of rest
8. Consider the flu vaccine
9. Stay home when you're sick

https://www.uhhospitals.org/Healthy-at-UH/articles/2014/03/9-tips-for-keeping-kids-germ-free-at-school



4

post_text:
Follow Five Steps to Wash Your Hands the Right Way
Washing your hands is easy, and it’s one of the most effective ways to prevent the spread of germs. Clean hands can stop germs from spreading from one person to another and throughout an entire community—from your home and workplace to childcare facilities and hospitals.

Follow these five steps every time.

Wet your hands with clean, running water (warm or cold), turn off the tap, and apply soap.
Lather your hands by rubbing them together with the soap. Lather the backs of your hands, between your fingers, and under your nails.
Scrub your hands for at least 20 seconds. Need a timer? Hum the “Happy Birthday” song from beginning to end twice.
Rinse your hands well under clean, running water.
Dry your hands using a clean towel or air dry them.
Why? Read the science behind the recommendations.

https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/show-me-the-science-handwashing.html

6A 2019-11-11. Here is a Public Service Announcement from the Iowa Department of Transportation: Please give us room to work. Snowplows don't operate like any other vehicle on the road. If you see a plow, don't tailgate it or drive along side it for any distance. Blowing snow makes it very hard for the driver to see you. If you are driving this morning, put your phone away.
